article.description: Cheryl Ford had 19 points and 18 rebounds to help the Shock beat the Liberty 87-82 in overtime Wednesday.
article.headline: Ford's double-double sparks Shock in OT
article.linkText: Ford, Nolan lead Shock past Liberty in overtime
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. -- Cheryl Ford had 19 points and 18 rebounds, and Deanna Nolan scored 21 points to help the Detroit Shock beat the New York Liberty 87-82 in overtime Wednesday.

Detroit's Kara Braxton, the Eastern Conference's starting center in the All-Star Game on Sunday, sat out with a sprained right ankle. Ford made sure the Shock didn't miss her in their fourth straight win.

"You judge yourself against the best, and we played with one of the best teams today," said Janel McCarville, who had 17 points and nine rebounds for the Liberty.

Both teams had a chances to go ahead in the last minute, but Ford and McCarville both missed short jumpers.

Neither team got off a shot on its final possession, sending the game into overtime.

Katie Smith's three-point play gave Detroit an early edge. After a New York miss, Ford split a pair of free throws, but Plenette Pierson grabbed an offensive rebound.

Nolan took advantage, hitting a jumper to make 78-72 with three minutes to go.

After Pierson hit one of two free throws, Detroit came up with another offensive rebound and Ford's layup put the game out of reach.

"I played everyone way too much today, but I felt it was very important to get a win coming out of the All-Star break, especially at home," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "Still, that will catch up with us down the road."

Swin Cash had 19 for the Shock, who had three starters play at least 42 minutes.

Ashley Battle also had 17 points for New York, but seven came in the final minute of overtime, after Detroit had built a 10-point lead.

"We knew we had to get aggressive and start attacking the basket again," Ford said. "That's how we play."

Detroit fell behind early, thanks to eight first-quarter turnovers, and trailed 39-33 at the half.

As has become their custom, they rallied in the third. This time, it was on the defensive end, as they held New York to just 13 points on 29 percent shooting in the quarter.

The Shock led late in the third, but former teammate Barb Farris hit a jumper in the final seconds to give her new team a 52-51 edge heading into the fourth.

The teams traded the lead 11 times in the first five minutes of the quarter, but Johnson's 3-pointer and Cash's jumper put Detroit ahead 67-63 with 4:12 left.

The Liberty's Shameka Christon had a three-point play to tie the game at 70 with 1:28 to go, setting up the dramatic finish.

"They made plays when they needed to make them, and we didn't," New York coach Pat Coyle said. "We've got to play better and we've got to play smarter."
